04681nam a22006615i 9780774855983DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20082007xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748559837 a10.59962/97807748559832doi  a(DE-B1597)662129  a(OCoLC)741348997  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aKE8910b.W45 2008 7aSOC0040002bisacsh04a345.71/042221 aWhite, Kimberley, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNegotiating Responsibility :bLaw, Murder, and States of Mind /cKimberley White. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2008] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLaw and Society00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Making and Mapping of Capital Murder Case Files -- tCriminological Thinking and Ways of “Knowing” the Criminal -- tNegotiating Responsibility in Law’s “Marketplace”: Beyond the Insanity Defence -- tThe Racialization of Criminal Responsibility -- tMurder between “Wives” and “Husbands” -- tConcluding Thoughts -- tAppendices -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tLaw and Society0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe meaning of criminal responsibility emerged in early- to mid-twentieth-century Canadian capital murder cases through a complex synthesis of socio-cultural, medical, and legal processes. Kimberley White places the negotiable concept of responsibility at the centre of her interdisciplinary inquiry, rather than the more fixed legal concepts of insanity or guilt. In doing so she brings subtlety to more general arguments about the historical relationship between law and psychiatry, the insanity defence, and the role of psychiatric expertise in criminal law cases. Through capital murder case files, White examines how the idea of criminal responsibility was produced, organized, and legitimized in and through institutional structures such as remissions, trial, and post-trial procedures; identity politics of race, character, citizenship, and gender; and overlapping narratives of mind-state and capacity. In particular, she points to the subtle but deeply influential ways in which common sense about crime, punishment, criminality, and human nature shaped the boundaries of expert knowledge at every stage of the judicial process. Negotiating Responsibility fills a void in Western socio-legal history scholarship and provides an essential point of reference from which to evaluate current criminal law practices and law reform initiatives in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCriminal liabilityxHistoryxCanada. 0aCriminal liabilityzCanadaxHistory. 0aForensic psychiatryxHistoryxCanada. 0aForensic psychiatryzCanadaxHistory. 0aInsanity (Law)xHistoryxCanada. 0aInsanity (Law)zCanadaxHistory. 0aMurderxHistoryxCanada. 0aMurderzCanadaxHistory. 0aTrials (Murder)xCanada. 0aTrials (Murder)zCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485598340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774855983423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774855983/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  